            "itemType": "journalArticle",
            "title": "Food Selection by Grey-headed Flying Foxes (Pteropus poliocephalus) Occupying a Summer Colony Site near Gosford, New South Wales",
            "creators": [
                {
                    "creatorType": "author",
                    "firstName": "K",
                    "lastName": "Parry-Jones"
                },
                {
                    "creatorType": "author",
                    "firstName": "Ml",
                    "lastName": "Augee"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "A colony site occupied by grey-headed flying-foxes (Pteropus poliocephalus) from October to May on\nthe central coast of N.S.W. was monitored over a 48 month period (1986-1990). Faecal and spat-out\nmaterial was collected for microscopic determination of contents. Comparison of food items in the\ndroppings with the array of possible food sources present in the vicinity of the colony at the same time\nshowed a marked preference for certain foods, in particular blossoms of the family Myrtaceae and of\nthe genus Banksia. Cultivated orchard fruits were not a preferred food and were only taken at times\nwhen preferred food items were scarce.",
